     <p><strong><p><strong>Alex Miller, <em>Wittgenstein and the Possibility of Meaning: “To Follow a Rule Blindly”</em>, Oxford University Press, 2024, 192pp., $90.00 (hbk) ISBN 9780192856487.</strong></p></strong></p>
     <p><strong>Reviewed by Paul Boghossian, New York University</strong></p>
     <p>Interest in the thought of the later Wittgenstein was hugely revived by Saul Kripke’s groundbreaking <em>Wittgenstein On Rules and Private Language, </em>first published in 1982. As is well known, in that book, Kripke developed a skeptical problem about the possibility of meaning and rule-following that he found in Wittgenstein’s later writings. The intuitive notion of following a rule that Kripke was working with can be summarized in terms of the following ACER model (see Boghossian 2008).</p> <p style="padding-left: 40px;">(Acceptance) If S is following rule R (‘If C, do A!’), then S has accepted (or ‘internalized’) R.</p> <p style="padding-left: 40px;">(Correctness) If S is following rule R, and it is the case that C, then S acts correctly if he does A; incorrectly otherwise.</p> <p style="padding-left: 40px;">(Explanation) If...
